[B] Belarus
Date: Thu 15 Dec 2022
Source: Pravda Gomel [in Russian, machine trans., edited]
https://gp.by/novosti/zdorove/news260727.html


The increase in the incidence of influenza this year [2022] was predicted for an earlier period, which is now being confirmed, Natalya Shmeleva, head of the laboratory of influenza and influenza-like diseases of the Republican Scientific and Practical Center for Epidemiology and Microbiology, told reporters.

Traditionally, an increase in the incidence of influenza in Belarus and in many countries is observed in January-February, but this year, as in the past, influenza viruses appeared a little earlier, Natalya Shmeleva noted. This situation is related to the coronavirus pandemic. "The emergence of the SARS-COV-2 virus and the development of the COVID-19 pandemic led to the fact that other respiratory viruses were forced out of the usual seasonal circulation. And in the 2020-2021 season, we practically did not register influenza viruses on a global scale, there were only sporadic cases ", said the head of the laboratory.

Later, the influenza virus returned to seasonal circulation and a 2-wave rise in the incidence was observed in the countries of the Northern Hemisphere. In the future, due to the spread of the omicron variant coronavirus, the epidemic rise in the incidence was short-lived and quickly subsided. "This year, we also predicted an earlier start of the epidemic rise in the incidence, which we are currently observing."

European countries have already entered the influenza epidemic since the 45th calendar week [week of 7 Nov 2022], in many countries the epidemic thresholds have long been exceeded both in terms of incidence and in the frequency of detection of influenza viruses," Natalya Shmeleva noted. According to her, influenza A (H3N2) viruses dominate globally, but in some countries, including Russia, and Belarus, A (H1N1) viruses predominate among detected influenza viruses. As the head of the laboratory explained, the different etiology of epidemic rises in the incidence in different countries is due to several reasons.

"First, we have been traveling less recently to the countries of North America and Europe, so the influenza virus that circulates there is less likely to enter our country. Second, in the countries of the Southern Hemisphere in the summer, when there was an epidemic rise in the incidence, influenza A (H1N1) and influenza B viruses circulating. This applies to a number of Asian countries.

The virus had the opportunity to get both to Russia and to Belarus. And now the H1N1 virus is predominantly spreading in our country. Cases of influenza B virus are also recorded, she said. Other respiratory viruses also contribute to the development of the epidemic situation. SARS-COV-2, respiratory syncytial virus, metapneumovirus, bocavirus, adenovirus, and parainfluenza are still relevant. That is, known viruses continue to circulate but only in certain periods of time the dominating place is occupied by different pathogens.

--
