[C] Bulgaria
Date: Fri 16 Dec 2022
Source: puls.bg [in Bulgarian, machine trans., edited]
https://www.puls.bg/novini-i-sbitiia-c-2/svinski-grip-u-nas-kakvo-sledva-n-46832


Three cases of swine flu have been established in Bulgaria. For the time being, the health authorities assure that there is no room for concern and emphasize that the most important thing is to limit infection among the population.

This was stated by the director of the National Center for Infectious and Parasitic Diseases Prof Iva Hristova in the program "Before Everyone" on Bulgarian National Radio.

"Anti-epidemic measures are helping, and now there is also an increase in viruses causing acute respiratory diseases, not only [influenza A/H1N1]. This is normal for the season, but this time it started earlier and with more sick people," explained Prof Hristova.

She emphasized that the respiratory syncytial virus, which is dangerous for newborns and for many of the elderly, takes the leading place with more frequent infections among people.

This is because in these target groups the disease is longer and more severe, and it is possible to develop bronchiolitis, to affect the respiratory function more seriously, and lead to hospitalization of the youngest children, up to 4 years.

"They have suffered because they do not have developed immunity, they are often in groups in kindergartens. This virus is also leading in the world. The measures are for parents to separate children from large groups of people, these are my recommendations. Also, we should not wait for the virus to develop and keep them from kindergarten, we should stop the child from contact with other children at the 1st symptoms. We have 2 antiviral preparations for this virus, but the flu vaccines do not protect us from it," explained Prof Hristova.

In 2nd place is the rhinovirus, again in children. Currently, there are also adenoviruses, parvoviruses, and others.

The director of the National Institute of Health and Welfare assured that it is not too late for those wishing to get the flu vaccine, as the peak of the season is expected in February and March.

"Negotiations are underway to purchase more flu vaccines; they are in demand worldwide at the moment. It is true that every year there are not enough, especially the free ones at the general practitioners' for the elderly," added Prof Iva Hristova for BNR.

[Byline: Christina Yordanova]

